segments.text: The boys were all in uniform, even the physically unfit boys wore a uniform with a NM on the collar, meaning non-military.
There were no women on the campus other than secretaries, and even some of the department heads had male secretaries at that time.
Before we start talking about Texas A&M, could I ask you a question about your decision to go into veterinarian sciences?
Was it just because you grew up with these cattle, and was it because you had a neighbor who was a veterinarian, or were there other reasons?
Well, that was the primary reason.
Who knows why a kid wants to be a college clown, a circus clown, or a railway engineer or whatnot?
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
The biggest thrill I ever got was when we went out and old Sal was trying to have pigs and the veterinarian's hand was too big.
And I went in and pulled the pigs out and I got two dollars.
I got it for that.
He charged five and he gave me two because I could help him.
And then he showed me how to clean out a horse's hoof and things like that.
And all three years I worked in the foundry, I still had the back of my mind that I was going to be a veterinarian someday.
Of course, they'd give me hands and arms.
Were there, when you were working in the foundry, were there any other professions that you ever considered?
No.
No, in fact, when I went to Kansas State, they offered me a year's
what do you call it, credit in engineering because of my foundry experience.
I'd taken correspondence course while I worked in the foundry, metalurgy and so forth, but I always wanted to be a veterinarian.
Okay, okay.
Now can you explain your
exactly what your functions or duties were when you came to Texas A&M?
I helped Dr. Smith.
Oh, you were his assistant.
Yeah.
I don't know whether you know it or not, but at that time there were three distinct entities on the A&M campus.
There was the Texas Agriculture Experiment Station, there was the Texas Agriculture Extension Service,
And there was a teaching college.
And each one had its own separate head.
And each one went to the legislature for its appropriation.
So in other words, for example, we had a Department of Veterinary, of Dairy Science.
We had an Experimentation Dairy Science.
And we had an Extension Service Dairyman.
They were not related to each other at all, administratively.
Of course informally, there was a lot of give and take.
Right, right.
But we worked in the Veterinary Science Department of the Texas Ag God's Experimentation
We worked on various diseases, including anthrax, brucellosis, mineral deficiencies, and parasitism.
And Dr. Smith was primarily interested in pathology and mineral deficiencies.
And he didn't care much for parasites.
He gave that to me as my baby.
And I became intensely interested in it and worked out a master's degree in biology because at that time there were no master's degrees in the School of Veterinary Medicine.
It was a school.
It wasn't a college.
It was a school.
And in 1937, they established a Department of Veterinary Parastrology in the School of Veterinary Medicine.
A Dr. H.L.
Van
We were on the same floor, the top floor of old Francis Hall.
And I often went to him with my problems and also helped him with some of his.
So I got
I should say I obtained quite a bit of formal parasitology without even realizing it.
And often I would take his classes when he was ill or out of town or whatnot.
And the more I delved into it, the more I became interested.
1938 I got a hearing aid and the whole world immediately changed its aspect.
This was a cumbersome thing.
The receiver was about three to six inches by an inch and a half and the battery pack weighed about a pound.
So I had Johnny
or what that Houston, Johnny Holly, built a harness for me.
Resembled nothing in the world more than an underarm holster to carry the batteries.
And we were at State Fair in 1939, my wife and I going around gawking, and a fella came up next to me
He said, I'd like to see you for a minute.
Well, he looked like he was big enough to.
At least he impressed me, and I said, well, what about?
He showed me his shield, and he said, let's step in here a minute.
He said, will you kindly unbutton your shirt?
He thought I was wearing a gun.
Really?
Under my left.
A shoulder holster.
Yeah.
That's what it really, that's what it looked like.
Well, with that hearing aid, I was quite relieved when I answered the telephone and I'd take the receiver and put it against the receiver's telephone against my receiver.
I remember I was over at Livingston one night and I wanted to make a call and I took the receiver and put it against my hearing aid and started talking to the
the transmitter.
A little Mexican boy went nuts there trying to tell me, no, no, no, you don't use it that way.
I finally opened my shirt and showed him.
He said, oh.
And I've had people come to my office and I had a piece of foam rubber in the top drawer of my desk.
And when the telephones rang, it was one of them old fast ones that
The receiver hung on the stand, you know.
I'd take the receiver off and drop it in the desk so I could lean against it.
And I'd just talk into the telephone.
And the time a county agent came in, the little boy, oh, he was little, I'd say he was 10 or 11.
Phone rang and I said, pardon me a minute.
I took the receiver off and dropped it in the desk drawer and leaned against it and started talking.
I had my hand free to use my pencil.
The kid looked up and said, I'll be goddamned.
So then I explained to him what I was doing.
And I'd go out to examine the animal.
I had an extra long cord on it.
I'd take it off and put it against the animal and use it as a test scope.
And it worked better than any I've ever had since.
Well, 1943.
Dr. Van Valkenburg died suddenly of a heart attack.
And they offered the department to me.
Actually, it was just a one-man department.
But I was making $3,600 a year with the experiment station.
The authority department was 4,500 so I took it with no regrets.
Dr. Smith was rather impatient with me but after all I'd worked for him nine years and I decided I could handle teaching with a hearing aid.
So then
Things rocked along.
What were you teaching then?
Peristalsis.
Veterinary peristalsis.
And also infectious and non-infectious diseases.
Okay, now can we stop for a moment and talk about teaching and the curriculum
back in the 1930s and the early 1940s.
Was there an overall aim of the vet program at that time?
Well, the overall aim then was primarily to turn out practitioners.
Right.
And they were, as I recall, six departments.
There was bacteriology.
Dr. Dunn, pathology doctor.
What's that guy's name?
Anyway, Dr. Jaggi was brought in in 1937 on public health.
I was teaching parapsychology.
Dr.
Lent was teaching clinic.
I can't think of the pathologist's name.
I'll think of it after a while.
Anyway, Dr. Marsteller was dean, and he also helped in the clinic.
And since parasitology was only two, three-hour courses, I also helped in the clinic.
In infected and non-infected diseases.
Then the war came along and we went up on what you call the speed-up program.
We took in a class every four months.
Instead of one every year?
Yeah.
Well, why was that?
Well, there weren't but about six or eight students in the class.
So some years, we had graduations three times a year.
In other words, the class of 45, some graduated in February and some along in April or May and some in September.
And the entire veterinary faculty was reduced to about 12 people.
From what was it before then, before the war?
Oh, about 15 or 20, I imagine.
Pardon me.
I'll tell you how many there are now.
Pardon me, I have to go to the bathroom.
Fine.
The name of the pathologist was Wharton, W-H-A-R-T-O-N. Now getting back to the war, did the war, did the war, was the federal government interested in increasing the number of veterinarians?
Is that why you tripled the program?
No.
We were just trying to get enough credit hours on the books to get our paper from the state.
In other words, we just had six boys in the class.
Well, how did you, how did you, uh...
I don't really know the reason for it.
I was just a, I was an old man on a toilet bowl then.
But I do know that we took, you can probably find someplace else, quiet.
Yeah, okay, fine.
But, fact remains, we took in the class every, every four months.
Okay.
In other, in any other ways did the war affect the vet school or your position?
Well no, except that of course we had trouble getting supplies and we had instructors leaving because they were in the reserve or draft.
For example, Dr. Armstead, Dr. Spangler, a whole bunch of them.
went in as officers.
That's why we're down to about 12, or at the most, 14.
Now getting back to the aim of the vet program, what did you think back in the late 1930s were the strong and weak points?
Well.
1930s see I didn't come here in 36.
Well that's yeah the late 1930s.
And I was in Experiment Station until 1943 so I really didn't have too much to do with it except that of course Experiment Station would try to find out why things happened.
Sure.
And try to elaborate or devise a message of bringing
disease under control, the good of veterinary medicine, I said, was primarily interested in turning out practitioners.
In fact, Dr. Marks used to say, get the boys out with the animals.
You can look at them flies on a cloudy day.
And he took a rather dim view of laboratory procedures as such.
but I don't really know.
Actually the school didn't begin to really boom until after the war when the GIs came back.
Now when you started teaching in 1943, let's talk for a minute about what courses you were teaching.
Well I was teaching

But in their parasitology, which includes the general conception of what parasites are, then parasites is a dog and cat, and parasites are cattle, and parasites are oranges, parasites are runes, sheep, goats, and cattle.
So it was
Active economic parasitology.
Let's see what... Oh, I see.
Parasites and parasitic disease.
That's the last one out.
It's a lot more complicated than the average person thinks.
Oh, looks tremendously complicated to me.
What were the major, back in those days, what were the major problems in the field with the parasites?
I mean, which were the major diseases that you were working to overcome?
The parasites in cattle and horses primarily, since cattle were the mainstay of the Texas ranchers.
and that includes knowledge of the drugs and the dosages.
We did a lot of work on trying out new drugs.
In fact, the first doses of several commonly used drugs were first at Texas A&M.
For example?
Yeah.
Well,
Oh, you have to watch me.
Phenothiazine, for example.
We were the first to show that phenothiazine could be poisonous to horses.
When about was that?
Oh, that was the 1940s.
1950s, thiobenzol, which is
a common wormer.
We also taught external parasites as well, horseflies, spaceflies, cattle grubs, lice, mites,

I would think that this would be one of the very important parts of the School of Veterinary Medicine because one of the main reasons it was founded was because of the parasitic problem with tick fever.
That's right.
And I saw the last group of cattle treated for tick fever over in Liberty County in 1936, shortly after I came here.
At that time, we used arsenical dips.
Of course, at the present time, it would be absolutely impossible to eradicate the Texas fever ticks because the federal government wouldn't let you use a compound as poisonous as arsenic.
But we didn't know it, and we went ahead and got rid of it anyway.
Trying to find the... How did the cattle withstand this dipping in arsenic?

Well, if it was done properly, there wasn't too much danger, but if they got a little bit too strong, of course you got arsenical burns, and there's no doubt that some of them died because they were weak and poor and
The actual physical trauma of running them through a dipping vat didn't do them any good.
I'm trying to find the... Oh, too much trouble.
Look at that.
I do want to show you something, though.
I'm a contributor to the last issue of the Merck Manual.
I've helped them since it started.
When did this start?
This is the Merck Veterinarian Manual.
I don't know.
I believe that's the fifth issue.
Maybe it's the fourth issue.
That's the last one.
Don't tell which issue it is.
Fifth.
Fifth, yeah.
It's the last.
It's the most recent one.
I worked on that last summer.
I have another question about when you started teaching back in 1943.
Can you describe the students?
Yes.
The students were, as a rule, much more serious than the general college.
Most of them came and took veterinary medicine because they wanted to be a veterinarian.
not for any financial gain or whatnot.

And it seemed to me like a lot of them, predominant, I believe, were people who had been closely associated with veterinary medicine, either their dad was a veterinarian or their uncle was a veterinarian or they had a brother who was a veterinarian or whatnot.
But veterinary students have always been
I don't know, less your college, you know the way I see it, than the students as a whole.
More serious.
More serious.
And veterinary medicine has always been pretty much of a tough course.
We used to say the only curriculum that was worse than veterinary medicine was taking up all the students' time was architecture.
Because the architects have to do all their drawings and
plans and things and have to take engineering and stresses and strains and so they were the only ones really that we felt like had to work as hard as we did.
Were there at this time back in the 1940s were there any women students?
No.
There were no women allowed in the college.
Yeah, yeah.
But I thought that at some professional schools, some women... Oh, at other schools there were.
There were women from Iowa, there were women from Kansas State, there were women from Philadelphia, there were women from Colorado.
In fact, there were two girls in school at the time I was back in 1930, in the 1930s.
At Kansas State.
Yeah.
Mm-hmm.
When were the first women allowed?
You'll have to check.
I believe Dr. Rutter let them in, what, in 1960?
I don't know.
I know I didn't have any women in any of my classes.
Okay, okay.
Okay, how about blacks?
Any blacks in the student body?
I mean in the veterinary college.
That's something I've never been able to understand.
Blacks are not particularly interested in blood and medicine.
There's, to my knowledge, there's never been a black, I mean, during my teaching years, there was never a black in school.
Kansas State, when I was there in the 30s, there was only one black boy and he flunked out his freshman year.
No, there were two.
One of them was Ted Williams, the lady with the
There were only two that I knew then.
And they've been made the same way, American Veteran Medical Association.
We have enough women to have an organization of their own, but there's no blacks to speak of.
Oh, I imagine it'd be less than 1% if I had to guess.
I doubt it's that high.
They want to, I don't know.
I'm just talking off the top of my head now.
It seems to me like they,
They want to be lawyers or doctors or something else.
But their medicine just don't appeal to them.
And I don't know why because I've known some black stable men out here at college that were really magicians with animals.
I know one man in particular who used to go into a horse stall with a rough heart and he'd quiet him down, talk baby talk to him and bring him out with no trouble at all.
Come to think of it, there's not even too many black jockeys.
There aren't, no.
I don't know why.
No, I don't either.
I don't know why.
You have to ask a black man.
Okay.
But we've never had blacks.
Now, they may have been one or two going through the years since I left there 12 years ago.
As far as the students...
What did you think the overall quality of the students, I know you talked about that they were hard workers, but the overall quality and intelligence, et cetera, did that change?
Well, I think it changed for the better because, I don't know, about 20 years ago, 15, everybody decided bed and medicine was a good deal.
I don't know why.
That's always been a mystery to me.
When I went to Kansas State, there were 40 boys in my class.
And about 10 of them were Kansans.
The rest of them were out of state.
And yet, all of a sudden, they came to the rest to get the veterinary medicine if they had to put a quote on it.
And they not only put a quote.
